 :tx/rationale "DEEP ANALYSIS: External mutation detection — first principles interrogation. The question is not 'how does the daemon detect external writes' but 'what is the correct coordination model when multiple processes share an append-only datom store?' Four candidate models: (A) Filesystem watch (inotify) — daemon polls OS for file events. Reactive, OS-dependent, misses events during daemon downtime, complex edge cases (rename vs write, buffering). (B) Transaction notification protocol — writers notify daemon via socket after writing. Requires all writers to know about daemon. Violates the filesystem-as-coordination principle. (C) Frontier comparison — on each query, daemon compares its frontier with disk frontier. If disk is ahead, apply new txns. Lazy, correct, but adds latency to reads. (D) The store IS the coordination — this is the DDIS answer. The shared store in txns/ is the coordination substrate (ADR-STORE-006). The daemon is a local cache, not the authority. On any operation that requires freshness (transact, merge), the daemon checks disk. On reads (query, status), the daemon serves from memory (possibly stale by one transaction). The staleness is bounded and disclosed."
